Vagrant Lab Operations Cheat-Sheet
# 1. Check VM Status
vagrant status

Lists all VMs and whether they are running, saved, or powered off.

# 2. Start / Bring Up VMs
    # Start all VMs (master, workers, Jenkins, Sonar)
    `vagrant up`

# Start a specific VM
    vagrant up k8s-master
    vagrant up k8s-worker1
    vagrant up k8s-worker2
    vagrant up jenkins-ci
    vagrant up sonarqube

# Use --provision to run updated provisioners:
    vagrant up --provision

# 3. Reload / Reprovision VMs

# 4.  Reload VM (reboot + run provisioners)
    vagrant reload --provision k8s-master

# 5. Reload all VMs
    vagrant reload --provision

Use this after updating Vagrantfile or scripts.

# 6. SSH Into a VM
    vagrant ssh k8s-master
    vagrant ssh k8s-worker1
    vagrant ssh k8s-worker2
    vagrant ssh jenkins-ci
    vagrant ssh sonarqube

After SSH, run commands like kubectl get nodes or check services.

# 7. Stop / Suspend VMs
    # Graceful shutdown of all VMs
    vagrant halt

    # Stop a specific VM
    vagrant halt k8s-master

# 8. Suspend (save state) instead of halting
    vagrant suspend

# 9. Destroy / Delete VMs
    # Destroy all VMs (clean slate)
    vagrant destroy -f

    # Destroy a specific VM
    vagrant destroy -f k8s-worker2

Warning: deletes VM disks and data.

7️⃣ Provision / Apply Changes
# Re-run provisioners for all VMs
vagrant provision

# Re-run provisioners for a specific VM
vagrant provision k8s-master

Useful after editing scripts/base.sh, Vagrantfile or inline provisioners (like kubeconfig fix).

8️⃣ Kubernetes Checks (inside k8s-master)
# Verify nodes
kubectl get nodes

# Verify all pods in all namespaces
kubectl get pods -A

# Deploy test nginx pod
kubectl run test-nginx --image=nginx --restart=Never --port=80
kubectl get pods -o wide

# Expose pod via NodePort
kubectl expose pod test-nginx --type=NodePort --port=80
kubectl get svc
